  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Six hours after a failed attempt, ground controllers re-established contact Thursday with the Hubble Space Telescope (HST)
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   through its main antennas. Controllers sent positional information to the telescope
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   and widened the radio beam
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   to cover a larger area around the two high-speed antennas.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Space shuttle Discovery trailed 57 miles behind the HST
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   and was to stay nearby until the Hubble's aperture door is opened Friday morning.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   If signals fail to open the door, astronauts will walk into space
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   and crank it open Saturday.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   The shuttle, scheduled to return to earth on Sunday, would extend its mission if the space walk is necessary.
  </a>
